  <hr />

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ednref1" name="_edn1" class="fn" id="_edn1">[i]</a> Rule 1.1 is entitled
  "Competence" and provides in pertinent part:</p>

  <p class="footnotetext">"(a) A lawyer shall provide competent representation to a client. Competent representation
  requires the legal knowledge, skill, thoroughness and preparation reasonably necessary for the representation."</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ednref2" name="_edn2" class="fn" id="_edn2">[ii]</a> Rule 8.4 is entitled
  "Misconduct" and provides in pertinent part:</p>

  <p class="footnotetext">"It is professional misconduct for a lawyer to:</p>

  <p class="footnotetext">"(a) Violate or attempt to violate the Rules of Professional Conduct, knowingly assist or
  induce another to do so, or do so through the acts of another."</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ednref3" name="_edn3" class="fn" id="_edn3">[iii]</a> At the oral argument, the
  Board directed the parties to address the applicability of the case <span class="cite"><i>In re Broome</i>, 92-3332
  (La. 3/26/93); <a  href="../SC/1993-03-26_1992-3332.htm">615 So.2d 1333</a></span>.Both parties argued
  that the facts of <i>Broome</i> are distinguishable from the case at hand and that the sanction imposed in
  <i>Broome</i>, a ninety day suspension, would be too harsh here.After careful consideration, the Board agrees that a
  ninety day suspension would be too severe in this matter.As pointed out by the parties, here the Respondent's
  misconduct was based on his failure to require the mortgagors to sign the documents in his presence, while Mr.
  Broome's misconduct was based on his gross negligence in supervising his employees, a violation of Rule 5.3.Further,
  Mr. Broome, who was charged with nine separate rule violations, failed to acknowledge the serious nature of the
  fraudulent conduct of his legal staff.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ednref4" name="_edn4" class="fn" id="_edn4">[iv]</a>The facts of this matter are
  difficult to evaluate under the language of the four standards relating to lack of competence, including Standard
  4.53, and their commentaries. However, since Respondent has admitted to lack of competence in this matter, Standard
  4.53 appears to be the one that most closely addresses the issues raised in this matter.</p>
  <hr />

  <div id="dissentLeake">
    <p class="headingstyle">Docket No. 00-DB-081</p>

    <p class="headingstyle">Andre P. Gauthier</p>

    <p class="headingstyle">Concurrence, with limited dissent:</p>

    <p class="Bodycopy"> The consent discipline public reprimand in this case carries eight conditions and provides
    that Respondent "shall be on probation until such time as the conditions ...have been fulfilled." I have a problem
    with condition (c) which requires Respondent to "perform fifty hours of <u>pro</u> <u>bono</u> legal services for
    the Capital Area Legal Services in the Twenty-Third District Court within the next twelve months." </p>

    <p class="Bodycopy">While I support and applaud <u>pro</u> <u>bono</u> legal services, I am uncomfortable with the
    notion of requiring <u>pro</u> <u>bono</u> services as a condition of probation in a disciplinary matter. Because
    Respondent has consented to it does not relieve the tension.</p>

    <p class="Bodycopy">Supreme Court Rule XIX, Sec. 10, provides for probation and requires only that the conditions
    of probation be in writing. The ABA Standards for Imposing Lawyer Sanctions (1991 Ed.) in its Commentary on Section
    2.7 says that "probation is a sanction that should be imposed when a lawyer's right to practice law needs to be
    monitored or limited rather than revoked." I believe that the commentary has been amended to say also that
    "probation is appropriate for conduct which may be corrected. "The commentary also says, "By imposing probation the
    Court allows a lawyer to continue to practice, but also requires the lawyer to meet certain conditions that will
    protect the public and assist the lawyer to meet ethical obligations."</p>

    <p class="Bodycopy">I recognize that RPC 6.1 says that "a lawyer should render public interest legal service," and
    I agree that condition (c) of the proposed probation certainly would assist Respondent to meet his ethical
    obligation under RPC 6.1, but I think it's clear that this disciplinary proceeding has nothing whatever to do with
    Respondent's RPC 6.1 duties. There is no showing whatever that Respondent does not meet such duties wholly
    independent of these proceedings. I doubt very strongly whether anyone is willing to use the disciplinary process
    to enforce RPC 6.1.I therefore think that condition (c) is improper and should not be a condition of probation.</p>

    <p class="signature">New Orleans, June 11, 2001.</p>

    <p class="signature">s/Robert E. Leake, Jr.</p>
